UNRELEASED
----------

* Cross-subcommand flag harmonization. Same letter for the same concept
  across scan/enr/me/ref/cmp wherever possible:
    -R   disable reverse-strand scoring (was -f in scan and enr).
    -N   motif sites / nsites override (was -n in scan).
    -t   hit-scoring p-value threshold (was -P in ref).
    -m   query motif file in cmp (was -q); -q now means q-value filter
         to match enr/me. yamenr's default q-value is now 0.1 (was 1.0)
         and is a compile-time DEFAULT_QVALUE_FILTER constant.
  All numeric defaults across scan/shuf/enr/me/ref/cmp are now #defines
  (added DEFAULT_HIT_PVAL, DEFAULT_STOP_PVAL, DEFAULT_MIN_W, DEFAULT_MAX_W,
  DEFAULT_N_MOTIFS, DEFAULT_DEDUP_OVERLAP in yamme; DEFAULT_HIT_PVAL,
  DEFAULT_R_PASSES in yamref).

* New -g flag in cmp/enr/me/ref: show a progress bar like yamscan's.
  Per-motif (enr/ref), per-query (cmp), per-width (me). Thread-safe via
  pthread mutex, suppresses per-motif -v/-w chatter while active.

* Help-text cleanup. Standardized on the "(default: X)" form across all
  subcommands. yamdedup's help condensed (dropped the column-aligned
  trailing whitespace and the overlong prose). yamscan's "-b <dbl,dbl,
  dbl,dbl>" shortened to "-b A,C,G,T" to match others.

* Total runtime printed under -v in every subcommand, with millisecond
  resolution via clock_gettime(CLOCK_MONOTONIC).

* yamtk scan/enr/cmp: -r (don't trim motif names) now also applies to MEME
  files. Previously the MEME name parser stopped at the first whitespace
  after "MOTIF", silently discarding the alt-name (e.g. "Arnt" in
  "MOTIF MA0004.1 Arnt"). The parser now captures the full
  "identifier altname" string; trim_motif_name (called when -r is not set)
  then truncates at the first space, preserving default behavior.

* yamtk ref: no longer trims motif names at all. MEME's "MOTIF id altname"
  is kept end-to-end, both in the [name] stderr summary lines and in the
  output MEME's MOTIF header. ref has no no-trim flag (its -r is taken
  by refinement passes).

* New subcommand: yamtk cmp — TOMTOM-equivalent query-vs-target motif
  comparison. Takes a query motif file (-q) and target motif database
  (-t), both in MEME/JASPAR/HOMER/HOCOMOCO. For each query x target it
  slides query columns against target columns at every valid offset
  (both orientations unless -R), scores the alignment with Pearson
  correlation (-d pcc, the only metric in v1; dispatch table set up so
  ED/SW/ALLR can be added later), and reports best-alignment p-values
  with per-query BH q-values. The null is the empirical distribution of
  PCC scores against actual database columns (TOMTOM-style; p-values
  match TOMTOM's within a small constant factor on JASPAR2026). For
  small target databases (< ~500 total columns) the empirical histogram
  becomes too sparse — use -e to switch to a parametric Dirichlet-
  Multinomial enumeration over a 56-column grid. Threading via -j over
  queries. TSV output columns: query_id, target_id, offset, p_value,
  q_value, score, overlap, query_consensus, target_consensus,
  orientation; sorted per-query by ascending q. -Q filters by q-value
  (default 0.1). -p applies a TOMTOM-style pseudocount before scoring
  (default 0; PCC is largely invariant to it but provided for
  compatibility); -N overrides every motif's nsites. Per-query PMFs are
  computed per-(start, length) window — not averaged — matching
  TOMTOM's get_pv_lookup_new structure. Deterministic; no RNG.

* yamtk scan/enr/ref/cmp MEME parser: handle JASPAR2026-style files.
  (1) URL trailer lines (e.g. "URL http://jaspar.elixir.no/...") after
  each PPM block are skipped via a positive numeric-line check instead
  of the previous '-'/'*' blacklist, which caught some URLs but not all.
  (2) Concatenated MEME files with repeated "MEME version", ALPHABET,
  "strands:" and "Background letter frequencies" headers now parse
  cleanly — the parser honors the first occurrence and emits one
  warning per repeated header type. The previous behavior was to abort
  with "Multiple alphabet definitions". (yamenr already had lenient
  behavior; warnings are new there too.)

* All subcommands: print "Total runtime: N.NNNs" with millisecond
  resolution under -v, using clock_gettime(CLOCK_MONOTONIC). Per-phase
  print_time calls (which suppress sub-2-second timings) are unchanged.

* New subcommand: yamtk ref — refine a seed motif against positive sequences.
  Takes a seed PWM (-m, accepting MEME/JASPAR/HOMER/HOCOMOCO) or an IUPAC
  consensus string (-1, e.g. CACGTG or NRTACGTYN), scans it against the
  positives, rebuilds the PWM from the resulting hit sites, and iterates
  for -r passes (default 2) with early-exit when the PWM stops changing.
  Flank operations: -e N adds N columns on each side on pass 1; -E walks
  out symmetrically one column at a time until both new flanks fall below
  the per-column IC threshold (-I, default 0.5 bits) and auto-trims any
  asymmetric dead column afterward; -T explicitly IC-trims at the end.
  Each motif gets an always-on stderr summary
  ([name] w: W1->W2 | IC: I1->I2 bits | hits: H1->H2) so users can tell
  refinement from drift. -Q drops motifs whose refined total IC is below
  seed IC. Outputs MEME v4 (default stdout, -o file). Multi-motif input
  is processed motif-by-motif; under-represented seeds (< MIN_REFINE_HITS,
  default 20) are dropped with a warning and the rest emitted.

* New subcommand: yamtk me — STREME-like de novo motif elicitation.
  Discovers enriched motifs from a positive FASTA against a negative
  set (or Eulerian-shuffled positives via -S).  For each width in
  [-k, -K] (default 6–15), enumerates canonical k-mers by Fisher's
  exact enrichment, builds and refines PWMs over the top seeds, masks
  hits, and iterates up to -N motifs per width.  Pooled motifs across
  widths are deduplicated by coverage overlap (-D), BH-FDR corrected,
  and filtered by q-value (-q, default 1e-3).  Low-information
  flanking PWM columns are trimmed at output, giving sharper
  consensus strings (e.g. TGASTCA instead of TTACTGAGTCAG for AP-1)
  and narrower MEME PWMs without changing p-values or hit counts.
  Consensus columns use IUPAC ambiguity codes (R/Y/S/W/K/M, B/D/H/V,
  N) when the smallest top-k base set covering CONSENSUS_THRESHOLD
  probability mass has more than one base, so degenerate motifs read
  naturally (e.g. RGGNNYTYCC → GGRARDBCCY).
  Outputs TSV stats (-o, default motifs.tsv) and MEME PWM file (-M,
  default motifs.meme).  -j enables per-width parallel discovery with
  deterministic output (same -s seed → byte-identical TSV regardless
  of -j).  Tunable compile-time macros (overridable via -D...):
  HAMMING_MISMATCH=1, REFINE_PASSES=2, TOP_K_SEEDS=4,
  MIN_REFINE_HITS=20, MIN_IC_BITS=0.5, CONSENSUS_THRESHOLD=0.75.

* yamshuf: added -x <BED> to restrict shuffling to BED-defined ranges.
  Bases inside ranges are shuffled in place; bases outside pass through
  unchanged. Sequences with no overlapping ranges are emitted unchanged.
  All four shuffle modes supported (Fisher-Yates, Euler, Markov, Linear);
  k-mer statistics are trained per range. Fully streaming — no
  whole-input buffering. Not compatible with -p.

* yamtk enr: removed sequence name duplicate checking; -d now only
  deduplicates motif names (duplicate sequence names are silently
  permitted). find_seq_dupes() and the associated char2maskindex /
  score_subseq_rev dead code have been removed.

* yamtk enr: NegSource field in the ##MotifCount header now reports
  "fasta" when a negative FASTA is supplied via -n, instead of leaking
  the input file path. Peak memory is no longer printed under -v.

CHANGES IN VERSION 2.1.0 (2026-05-07)
--------------------------------------

* Condensed -h output for all subcommands (scan, shuf, enr) to fit on one
  screen; wording and formatting now consistent across all three.

* New subcommand: yamtk enr — motif enrichment scoring.
  Compares a positive FASTA against a negative FASTA (or an in-process
  shuffled-positive null) for each motif in a MEME/JASPAR/HOMER/HOCOMOCO
  file. Three test modes via -T:
    seqs    — one-tailed Fisher's exact test on per-sequence hit presence.
    sites   — one-tailed Fisher's exact test on per-position hit rate.
    ranksum — threshold-free Mann-Whitney U on per-sequence max PWM score
              (AUC effect size; tie-corrected normal approximation).
  All modes always report both per-sequence and per-site hit counts.
  BH FDR correction applied across all motifs in the run (-q filter).
  Supports gzipped input, multi-threading (-j), custom backgrounds (-b),
  and all four motif formats supported by yamtk scan.
  Full flag set matches yamtk scan: -p (pseudocount), -N (nsites, uppercase
  to avoid conflict with -n for negatives FASTA), -d (deduplicate names),
  -r (do not trim names to first word).

CHANGES IN VERSION 2.0.1 (2026-05-02)
--------------------------------------

* Fixed 21 bugs identified by a systematic audit of all three tools.
  Highlights:

  yamscan:
  - Fixed verbose BED scan log printing garbage coordinates due to using
    the motif loop index instead of the BED region index for bed.starts[]
    and bed.ends[].
  - Fixed add_seq_name checking the name length after writing into the
    destination buffer (guard was dead code); also fixed a pre-existing
    use-after-free reading kseq fields after kseq_destroy.
  - Fixed kseq_t being leaked in the low-mem scanning path (also removed
    an erroneous free of kseq-owned memory) and in the threaded path.
  - Fixed malloc(sizeof(uint64_t *)) that should be sizeof(uint64_t) for
    thread index allocation (harmless on 64-bit, UB on 32-bit ports).
  - Fixed get_meme_bkg error messages that named 'C' when the parser had
    encountered a misplaced G or T/U character.
  - Duplicate -s and -o flags now exit with a clear error instead of
    silently reopening the file and leaking the first handle.

  yamdedup:
  - Fixed check_field_size accepting fields of exactly FIELD_MAX_CHAR
    (512) bytes, which extract_field had already dropped to empty; such
    fields now produce a clear error.
  - Duplicate -i and -o flags now exit with a clear error.
  - Fixed a crash in cleanup when badexit was called before the hash
    table was initialised.

  All tools:
  - Replaced all %llu / %'llu printf format specifiers with PRIu64 /
    %'" PRIu64 " from <inttypes.h> for C99 portability.

* Added an automated test suite (make check / make check-debug). Tests
  cover smoke tests, happy-path functional behaviour for all three
  subcommands, and regression cases for all 21 fixed bugs. The debug
  target rebuilds with AddressSanitizer and UndefinedBehaviorSanitizer
  before running the suite. CI now runs both targets on every push.


CHANGES IN VERSION 2.0.0 (2025-10-18)
--------------------------------------

* Merged yamscan, yamshuf, and yamdedup into a single binary: yamtk.
  Subcommands are invoked as yamtk scan, yamtk shuf, and yamtk dedup.
  The individual tools are no longer distributed separately.

* Fixed several bugs identified since yamscan 1.7 / yamshuf 1.2:
  - Fixed 12 critical and important bugs in yamscan (motif parser
    overflows, realloc NULL checks, BED off-by-ones, uint64 underflow,
    score sorting non-determinism, negative argument acceptance).
  - Fixed 4 critical bugs in yamdedup (realloc sizeof, early eviction
    trigger, tiebreak non-determinism, p-value validation).
  - Fixed 2 bugs in yamshuf (shuffle_linear tail skip and bias,
    shuffle_euler terminal vertex edge corruption).

* Improved tolerance of the BED reader to leading/trailing whitespace
  characters on a field boundary (yamscan, 2025-02-13).

* Minor Makefile and compilation warning cleanups.


CHANGES IN YAMSHUF 1.3 (2023-11-30)
-------------------------------------

* Small performance improvement to sequence shuffling throughput.


CHANGES IN YAMSCAN 1.7 / YAMSHUF 1.2 (2023-09-11)
----------------------------------------------------

* Added sequence masking to yamscan (-g / --mask). Masked (lower-case)
  bases are skipped during scanning; hits overlapping masked positions
  are suppressed.

* Updated the random number generator in yamshuf from xoroshiro128+ to
  xoroshiro128++ 1.0 for improved statistical quality.


CHANGES IN YAMSHUF 1.1 (2023-08-15)
-------------------------------------

* Added -p flag to print k-mer counts alongside shuffled sequences.

* Disallowed tab characters in -p output columns.


CHANGES IN YAMSCAN 1.6 / YAMSHUF 1.0 (2023-08-14)
----------------------------------------------------

* Added yamshuf: a fast k-mer-preserving sequence shuffler. Supports
  four shuffling methods:
  - Fisher-Yates (k=1, default)
  - Eulerian path shuffle (k>1, exact k-mer composition preservation)
  - Markov chain shuffle (-m)
  - Linear k-mer shuffle (-l)
  Accepts gzipped FASTA/FASTQ input; uses xoroshiro128+ for random
  number generation; memory scales exponentially with k (max k=9).

* Added utility script std_kmers.sh for k-mer frequency analysis.

* Fixed a BED scanning loop bug in yamscan where the final valid window
  in a BED interval was skipped due to an off-by-one (< instead of <=
  in the loop bound).


CHANGES IN YAMSCAN 1.5 / YAMDEDUP 1.0 (2022-12-02)
-----------------------------------------------------

Note: minimotif was renamed yamscan at this release; a companion
deduplication tool yamdedup was added at the same time.

* Added yamdedup: deduplicates overlapping hits from yamscan output,
  keeping the highest-scoring hit per (sequence, motif, strand)
  combination. Accepts yamscan TSV output or generic BED input.
  Low peak memory via chunk-based streaming. Uses khash for
  sequence/motif/strand bucketing.

* Switched yamscan internal data structures to khash for sequence and
  motif name lookups; safer string-to-number conversion throughout.

* Post-release bugfixes:
  - Fixed type widths (uint64_t/size_t) throughout yamscan and yamdedup.
  - Fixed a BED scanning loop that skipped hits in the final window of
    each interval (partially; full fix in yamscan 1.6).

* Added utility scripts: flip_rc.sh, to_gtf.sh, to_gff3.sh.


CHANGES IN MINIMOTIF 1.3 (2022-11-04)
---------------------------------------

* Cleaned up and prettified output formatting.

* Removed the -L flag.


CHANGES IN MINIMOTIF 1.2 (2022-10-25)
---------------------------------------

* Added BED-restricted scanning (-x). Sequences are only scored within
  the intervals specified by the BED file; all output coordinates refer
  to positions within the BED ranges.

* Added to_bed.sh utility script for converting output to BED format.

* Added progress reporting to the companion deduplication workflow.


CHANGES IN MINIMOTIF 1.1 (2022-09-10)
---------------------------------------

Note: the tool was distributed as minimotif at this time and later
renamed yamscan / yamtk.

* Added utility post-processing scripts.

* Various documentation improvements.


CHANGES IN MINIMOTIF 1.0 (2022-01-21)
---------------------------------------

Note: initial public release under the name minimotif.

* Fast multi-threaded motif scanner for DNA/RNA sequences. Accepts
  FASTA/FASTQ input (plain or gzipped). Scores every position using a
  P-value CDF lookup table built from the PWM and a background model.

* Supports MEME, JASPAR, HOMER, HOCOMOCO, and consensus motif formats.

* Low-memory mode (-l) processes sequences one at a time instead of
  loading all sequences into memory.

* Prints sequence composition statistics when no motifs are provided.

* Added JASPAR pseudocounts for columns summing to zero.

* Linux compatibility; replaced ad-hoc sequence reading with kseq.h.

* Performance improvements: memory allocation in chunks, reduced realloc
  calls, slight CDF fill speedup.
